abstract = {The Human Connectome Projects in Development ({HCP}-D) and Aging ({HCP}-A) are two large-scale brain imaging studies that will extend the recently completed {HCP} Young-Adult ({HCP}-{YA}) project to nearly the full lifespan, collecting structural, resting-state {fMRI}, task-{fMRI}, diffusion, and perfusion {MRI} in participants from 5 to 100+ years of age. {HCP}-D is enrolling 1300+ healthy children, adolescents, and young adults (ages 5-21), and {HCP}-A is enrolling 1200+ healthy adults (ages 36-100+), with each study collecting longitudinal data in a subset of individuals at particular age ranges. The imaging protocols of the {HCP}-D and {HCP}-A studies are very similar, differing primarily in the selection of different task-{fMRI} paradigms. We strove to harmonize the imaging protocol to the greatest extent feasible with the completed {HCP}-{YA} (1200+ participants, aged 22-35), but some imaging-related changes were motivated or necessitated by hardware changes, the need to reduce the total amount of scanning per participant, and/or the additional challenges of working with young and elderly populations. Here, we provide an overview of the common {HCP}-D/A imaging protocol including data and rationales for protocol decisions and changes relative to {HCP}-{YA}. The result will be a large, rich, multi-modal, and freely available set of consistently acquired data for use by the scientific community to investigate and define normative developmental and aging related changes in the healthy human brain. Copyright \copyright 2018 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.}
